# DotLearn project rules

## Architecture

- This is a **modular monolith inside a pnpm workspaces monorepo**. Frontend (`apps/web`) and backend (`apps/api`) are separate workspaces and never import from each other directly. The shared boundary is `packages/contracts`.
- Topics under `topics/<slug>/` are **content**, not code. They never import from `apps/*`.
- `packages/contracts` is the single source of truth for types and validation. Schemas defined as Zod, types derived via `z.infer<>`.

## Frontend rules (`apps/web`)

- React 18, TypeScript strict, functional components only.
- Vite for dev/build. Topics are loaded via `import.meta.glob`.
- Routing: TanStack Router.
- Styling: Tailwind CSS, no inline styles.
- Sandbox execution lives in `packages/sandbox` and runs in Web Workers.
- All AI calls go through `packages/ai-providers` (BYOK). Keys stored in IndexedDB, never sent to a server.

### Responsive design (mobile + desktop, mandatory)

- Every new page or component ships for **both mobile and desktop in the same change**. Mobile-first Tailwind: base classes target narrow screens, `sm:`/`md:`/`lg:`/`xl:` widen the layout.
- Touch targets are at least 44px: use the `--tap` / `--tap-comfort` tokens, never magic numbers. Primary action buttons go full-width on mobile (`w-full sm:w-auto` or `flex-1 sm:flex-initial`).
- Text inputs use 16px font on mobile (`text-[16px] sm:text-sm` or the `form-input` class) so iOS Safari does not zoom on focus.
- Hover-only affordances must not be load-bearing: Tailwind is configured with `hoverOnlyWhenSupported`, and pointer-tracking effects bail out on `(pointer: coarse)`.
- Below `md` the bottom tab bar (`BottomTabBar`) is the primary navigation; pages must not place fixed UI in its zone (`--mobile-tabbar-h` + `--safe-bottom`).
- Wide content (tables, result grids, viz) gets `overflow-x-auto` instead of forcing horizontal page scroll. No unconditional `min-w-*` — scope it to a breakpoint (`sm:min-w-[…]`).
- Verify every UI change at 375px and 1280px (DevTools device emulation) before considering it done.

### Content-loading budget

- Topic content (MDX theory, YAML exercises) and heavy dependencies (Monaco, runtimes) are loaded lazily. Never add an eager `import.meta.glob` over `topics/**` or a static import of a heavy editor/runtime into a shared chunk.
- New routes are code-split (`React.lazy` in `router.tsx`); only `HomePage` stays in the entry chunk.
- Per-topic aggregates for list pages come from the build-time `virtual:topic-stats` module, not from loading topic bundles.

## Backend rules (`apps/api`)

- NestJS with Layered DDD: `domain/`, `infrastructure/`, `dto/` per module.
- Controllers handle HTTP only. Business logic lives in services. Persistence behind injected interfaces.
- Validation via `class-validator` with strict whitelisting on every DTO.
- Global response interceptor (`ResponseInterceptor`) and global exception filter (`AllExceptionsFilter`).
- Swagger decorators on every endpoint.
- Structured logging via pino; no `console.log`.
- Future financial features must use a ledger pattern and an idempotency service. No `increment()` / `decrement()` on balances.

## Code style

- **No comments in code.** Express intent through names and types. Comments allowed only in MDX prose, not in code blocks.
- No emojis in source or content unless explicitly requested.
- Names are descriptive: `submissionStatus`, not `s` or `status`.
- Errors are typed. Throw domain-specific error classes, not bare `Error`.

## Adding new topics

Use the `lesson-forge` skill at `.cursor/skills/lesson-forge/SKILL.md`. Never invent a topic structure ad-hoc — the skill encodes the contract and runs the validation pipeline.

## Adding new exercise types

Requires a coordinated change across three places **in one PR**:

1. `packages/contracts/src/exercise.schema.ts` — Zod variant
2. `packages/lesson-engine/src/runners/` — runner implementation
3. `.cursor/skills/lesson-forge/schemas/exercise.schema.json` + `reference/exercise-types.md`

If you cannot do all three in one change, do not start.

## Commits

- Conventional commits.
- One topic per commit when adding content.
- Squash agent-generated commits unless they represent meaningfully separate units of work.
